"Train?  What train?!!  There are ONLY twelve of them!"</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/unekrotic.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Nekrotic</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>p0\/\/3r-p0sT3r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/5/02 1:43:02 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=48>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> Adding content itself to the game will not change matters.  It's the type of content added and how it is implemented.<br>
<br>
Some of us have been playing for 2+ years now, yet I bet we all can name zones we have never set foot into....the content is there but remains unused.  I would venture to guess most people playing really spend most of their time in 5-10 zones.<br>
<br>
The problem is one of availability.  Verant purposefully creates a bottleneck by making a few zones highly desirable.  This forces everyone to compete for those zones.....in the old days it was Naggy/Vox, then Plane of Fear/Hate, then Veeshan's Peak, then NTOV....next stop who knows.<br>
<br>
The content is already there, but it can't be shared because it can be reached too easily by too few.  I don't know if there is any real solution to this, giving that Verant's philosophy on these matters is easy to see just by how the game is designed.<br>
<br>
I would say however that the best way to decrease competition would be to make sure the competition doesn't have to be forced into confrontations with each other.<br>
<br>
One simple way would be to make the &quot;uber&quot; mobs much more difficult to reach or kill.  It's kinda silly that one of the hardest zones in the game can be farmed by a single guild in a few hours.  If the zone was made more difficult or time consuming (like Plane of Air), then that would tie up one guild for a whole day or weekend.  People don't go to Plane of Air because the amount of time necessary to invest doesnt match the rewards - in fact if it wasn't for the epic quest mobs, PoA would probably be empty.  Yet, if PoA had mobs as hard as NTOV, with the same quality of drops....then I would think it would be worthwhile for a raiding guild to spend a whole weekend in PoA.....and therefore that would take 1 guild out of the rat race of having to compete for other spawns....create a few zones like this and keep people busy and out of each other's hair, instead of having to race each other to kill uber mobs that a guild can drop in 5 minutes.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
