Now to the issue of Quests, not every quest with a half decent reward needs to drop off some uber mob.  The Coldain Prayer Shawl Quest is one such quest that illustrates that.  I also happen to like the Phenocryst Focus Quest.  However, VI needs to implement more quests that don't require a raiding force, and instead require more thinking.  Stop adding things like Gems and Everquest Legends and spend some time on content is all I'm saying to VI. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ushallandra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shallandra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/6/02 10:29:34 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=55>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The best thing Verant could do is to randomize the spawns in NToV. Make a few of the mobs spawn each day, preferably ones in different sections of North, and you solve parts of the bottleneck problem that you have with one guild killing everything. If they wanted every mob in North, they would have to spend a decent amount of time there each day, taking them out of the picture on some of the other mobs that spawn later in the week and spreading the wealth a little, so to speak.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
