As for the 7th coldain shawl and 9th rings, I agree that both of these quests can be done with one good group, and I also agree that they are done frequently. However, the items are middle high-end items, not end game items like NTOV drops are. I would venture that most people who have these items will end up switching them out for NTOV or items dropped from ubers when they get the chance. <p>Aaaieee! Beasties die, yub!</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ushallandra.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shallandra</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>h0x0r!</span><br> <font color=#000033>(2/6/02 11:55:39 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/feqasylumrantsandravesbalancingissues.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1641.topic&index=58>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: The Death of EQ's Casual-Raid Playerbase</span><hr size=1> Though I have to admit it would be interesting to have open ended advancement, it is not feasible for EQ.  Reasons why:<br>
<br>
Existing Content: Content is defined, a great deal, by levels.  Verant wants some encounters to be <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> very</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> difficult, if not downright impossible.  They do this by limiting the skills, HP, and other statistics a character can acquire.  This puts limits on characters, and defines the challenge in a high end game.<br>
<br>
Skills:  Skills will never go above 255.  This isn't a magical number Verant invented, its a memory consideration.  One bye can hold a value from 0 to 255 (256 possible values).  To store a number larger than 255 the program would have to use a long integer.  Long integers use memory in relation to the bit-depth of the host machine.  On a 32-bit system, a long integer is 32 bits, or 4 bytes (this is a generalization, there are some machines on which this actually varies).  Its not that big a deal on the client side; your machine can handle it.  On the server side though, where a machine can be handling hundreds, if not thousands, of characters this is a very sizeable issue.  Thus, skills will probably never be allowed to advance beyond 255, and if skills can't go beyond 255, it is doubtfull you would see much improvement from leveling beyond 60.<br>
<br>
There are other factors as well, but the two above are what prevents EQ from being open-ended, that I can see. <p>Shallandra McKnight, Uba Monkey<br>
Zassazy Moonkiepett, Sexy Leezard Shaman<br>
Daxes Solvaires, Naughty Flute Girl<br>
